{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01WbyGcX36XeyKM2eiwywJ1P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me design the implementation:\n\n## What needs to happen\n\nThe task is to implement a content-hash-triggered rolling restart for the CNO-injected CA ConfigMap in the IstioCSR controller, mirroring the pattern in trustmanager.\n\nIn the trustmanager:\n1. `createOrApplyDefaultCAPackageConfigMap()` reads the CNO-injected CA bundle, computes a SHA-256 hash of the PEM data, and returns the hash string.\n2. The hash is passed to `createOrApplyDeployment()` → `getDeploymentObject()` → `updateDefaultCAPackageVolume()`.\n3. `updateDefaultCAPackageVolume()` stamps the hash as a pod template annotation, so when the hash changes, the deployment gets updated and triggers a rolling restart.\n4. The `deploymentModified()` function compares pod template annotations to detect these changes.\n\nFor istiocsr, I need to follow the same pattern: create a function to read and hash the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap, then pass that hash through to annotate the pod template so changes trigger a rolling restart. The idempotency guard is already built in—if the annotation stays the same because the ConfigMap hasn't changed, `hasObjectChanged` returns false and skips the update. I need to verify that `deploymentSpecModified()` actually compares pod template annotations, since it currently only checks labels. For the annotation key itself, I'm considering `cert-manager.io/ca-bundle-hash` or `operator.openshift.io/ca-bundle-hash` to keep it consistent with the trustmanager pattern.\n\nLooking at the troubleshooting docs, `cert-manager.io/ca-bundle-hash` is the right choice since it's already documented there. My plan is to create a new file with functions to read the CA bundle from the operator namespace and compute its SHA-256 hash, mirroring how trustmanager handles this.\n\nBut I'm realizing the istiocsr controller gets CA data from different sources—user-provided ConfigMaps or issuer secrets—whereas the task specifically asks for the CNO-injected bundle. I need to read from `common.TrustedCABundleConfigMapName` in `common.OperatorNamespace`, hash the PEM content, and apply that hash annotation to the pod template to trigger rolling restarts when the CA changes.\n\nI'm mapping out the implementation: a new file for reading and hashing the CA bundle, a constant for the annotation, and modifications to the deployment creation logic to include and apply the hash.\n\nThe existing idempotency pattern in `createOrApplyDeployments` already handles this—once I add pod template annotation comparison to `deploymentSpecModified`, the check will naturally skip updates when the hash hasn't changed, which serves as the idempotency guard. The idempotency guard is already in place structurally - I just need to ensure the hash annotation comparison is part of the `deploymentSpecModified` check. Now I'm planning out the new files, starting with a ConfigMaps handler that reads the CNO-injected CA bundle from the operator namespace and computes its hash. Writing Go code...\n\nI also need to handle the case where the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap might not exist yet, since reading it could fail in the trustmanager.  I think the right approach is to attempt reading the ConfigMap, but if it's not found, I'll just skip the hash computation and log a message rather than failing the entire reconciliation—since this is an OpenShift-specific feature that might not be available on all clusters.\n\nLooking back at the task description, it assumes the CNO-injected CA ConfigMap exists, so I should probably follow the trustmanager pattern more closely and return an error if the read fails. But I need to be careful here because the istiocsr controller already manages its own CA ConfigMap, so I need to understand how these two interact before implementing the rolling restart logic.\n\nThe key insight is that the CNO-injected CA bundle is separate from the controller's own CA ConfigMap. The flow should be: read the CNO bundle, hash its content, stamp that hash onto the istio-csr deployment's pod template, and let the existing ConfigMap watch trigger reconciliation when the hash changes. But first I need to verify whether the istiocsr controller is already watching the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap.\n\nLooking at the controller's watch setup, it filters ConfigMaps by checking for specific labels—either the managed resource label or the watch label. The CNO-injected CA bundle won't have either of these labels, so it won't trigger reconciliation on its own.\n\nThe trustmanager reads the ConfigMap during reconciliation and computes a hash to detect changes. Since the CA bundle is in the operator namespace while reconciliation happens in the istiocsr namespace, I need to figure out what mechanism actually triggers the reconciliation when the CA bundle updates. Let me focus on the core task: reading the config and handling the CA bundle appropriately. Writing the ConfigMap handler... Writing error handling and validation... Adding the CA bundle hash annotation constant that tracks changes to trigger pod restarts, then modifying the deployment functions to accept and apply this hash to the pod template annotations, and finally updating the install logic to read the hash before creating deployments.\n\nIn the utilities, I need to add annotation comparison to the deployment modification check, using a map equality function to properly handle nil versus empty map cases. Actually, `maps.Equal` does treat nil and empty maps as equivalent since they both have length zero, so that shouldn't cause false positives in practice—the first update with a non-empty hash will correctly trigger the change.\n\nFor the annotation key, I'll use `cert-manager.io/ca-bundle-hash` as mentioned in the troubleshooting docs. Now I need to updat